\textbf{CHIEF COMPLAINT:}
60-year-old right-handed male referred for evaluation of numbness and tingling in both hands.

\textbf{HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:}
The patient reports numbness and tingling in both hands which have worsened over the past month. He attributes this to a car accident he had last December which resulted in a contusion to his head and bilateral wrist fractures. He wears splints on both wrists, but they are still symptomatic. He has mild stiffness in his neck. He describes the numbness and tingling as from the middle and ring finger on the right side and pinky and ring finger on the left side. The symptoms are mainly sore and weak, and he experiences throbbing at times. Symptoms are more prominent at night and intermittent throughout the day. He denies any loss of sensation. Patient also reports some musculoskeletal pain and nail changes.

\textbf{REVIEW OF SYSTEMS:}
Fatigue, weight gain, excessive appetite, bloating, floaters, shortness of breath, leg swelling, always hungry, nail bed changes, dryness, itching, muscle pain. The remainder of the review of systems is negative.

\textbf{PHYSICAL EXAMINATION:}
Normal except for: 
- Sensation is diminished in the third and fourth fingers on the right hand and decreased in the fourth and fifth fingers on the left hand.
- Reflexes are 1+ symmetric, 2+ knees; toes are downgoing bilaterally.
- Tinels sign is positive at wrists and elbows bilaterally.

\textbf{ASSESSMENT AND PLAN:}
Assessment is consistent with bilateral carpal tunnel syndrome, potentially bilateral cubital tunnel syndrome. Likely bilateral carpal tunnel syndrome given the history and examination findings. To further evaluate, order nerve conduction studies to determine the location of irritation. Depending on the test results, possible referral to hand clinic for injections or carpal tunnel release surgery or orthopedist for similar management. Splints should be continued.

\textbf{INSTRUCTIONS:}
Patient advised to continue wearing splints. Nerve conduction studies and EMG planned, followed by further management based on results. Follow-up after nerve conduction studies are done.

\section*{CHIEF COMPLAINT}
Patient presents with chronic lumbar back pain.

\section*{HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS (HPI)}
The patient reports experiencing back pain for a couple of years after falling hard during a basketball game. The pain is sharp and is rated as a seven out of ten on the pain scale. It radiates down the left leg, and the patient has numbness in the toes. The pain worsens with standing and improves when lying down. The patient describes some incontinence and weakness in the lower limbs. The patient has tried injections and physical therapy in the past with limited success. 

\section*{REVIEW OF SYSTEMS}
Negative except as mentioned in the HPI.

\section*{PHYSICAL EXAMINATION}
Vitals reviewed and no abnormal findings. On examination, there is tenderness at the L4-L5 disk space and right-sided lumbar paravertebral tenderness. Straight leg raise test positive. Decreased sensation to light touch at the right lateral thigh with symmetrical patellar and Achilles reflexes. No motor deficits noted.

\section*{RESULTS}
MRI results indicate disk desiccation, disk bulge with paracentral disk herniation resulting in moderate right for neural foraminal stenosis. 

\section*{ASSESSMENT AND PLAN}
The patient has a herniated disk at the L4-L5 with radiculopathy. A spinal injection with corticosteroid is recommended. A prescription for an anxiolytic will be sent to help with the anxiety related to the procedure. If pain persists post-injection, pain medications may be considered.

\section*{INSTRUCTIONS}
The patient is to schedule a spinal injection with the front desk. They will need to take the anxiolytic medication as prescribed before the appointment.

